            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "I canceled the vim PR.\n\nAfter digging more into this topic, I would like to share following important points:\n\n1.) **regular vim lua indent** uses regexes to find keywords (like if/else etc) to determinate which indent should be used\n   Those regexes also match keywords inside of code regex statements, which shouldn't be treated like keywords for indent but like a string\n   For example:  `[[^\\s*\\%(if\\>\\|BUT_IM_A_USER_CODE_REGEX\\>\\)]]` ==> found `if` -> triggers indent\n   That's a missbehaviour which shoudn't be adopted from vim.\n\n2.) **regular vim lua indent** forces lines inside a comment block \"--[[ ... ]]--\" to be left aligned/indented.\nThat is bad in my opinion. Everything inside a comment block shouldn't be touched at all. ==> obvious assumption\n\n`nvim-treesitter'.indentexpr()` handles those points correctly.\nMaybe a small improvement could be, that opening and closing tag of comment block are aligned to eachother - but that's peanuts\n\nWe can discuss if the content in comment-blocks could be indented as well, so it differs from multiple single comment lines\n(I like this idea for better readability of code: Text Blocks are single-line comments, \"disabled\" but indented Code inside of comment-blocks)\nBut that is not what others expect it should be and what the spec defines...)\n==> Comment blocks shouldn't be touched at all\n\nBecause of point 1.) we should not mix up regex-parsing and treesitter together. A proper solution must handle user-regex case!\nWe already have the tokenized AST from treesitter, so we should use it. More robust.\nAre there show-stopper that prevent to take nvim-treesitter'.indentexpr() into core? This is a working solution.\n\n_On large lua files the ts-indent takes more time than the regex-indent.\nI didn't looked into the code, but it could be something like a loop on every line like this:\n\"<<from current line, goto previous line until found a (comment)-boundary. same in the other direction>>\"\nMaybe this is worth to be improved._\n\nNevertheless, I could provide a small indent/lua.lua which is mostly the vim-implementation, that fixes initial issue (Single-Line-Comments are wrong indented)\nIt doesn't require treesitter, but it doesn't fix:\n1.) the match of an user defined regex with keywords inside the code\n2.) indents comment blocks as regualar code and not as untouched plain text. Inside it, a leading `end` tag/text is miss-indented, because this tag is always shifted one left in relation to the previous line. This rare edge case could be neglected, but the commentblock behaviour in general is \"breaking\"\n\nI think the best solution would be, that nvim-treesitter'.indentexpr() becomes core.\n\n",
